egemann, Caitlin Moran, Charlotte Roche, Emma Jane Unsworth, Kate Zambreno, and Juli Zeh, among others. These texts illustrate the complex processes by which female subjects become women today. Failure, refusal, disgust, and anger are striking features of these becomings. Drawing on the work of Sara Ahmed (Willful Subjects) and thinkers including Simone de Beauvoir, Rosi Braidotti, and Elizabeth Grosz, the book demonstrates the significance of willfulness for understandings and assertions of female agency. In addition, it proposesa view of literary works themselves as instances of willfulness. The book will be of interest to scholars working in comparative literature, English, German studies, and feminist, gender, and queer studies. Emily Jeremiah is Senior Lecturer in German and Gender Studies at Royal Holloway, University of London.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAmerican fictionxHistory and criticism. 0aComparative literaturexAmerican and German. 0aComparative literaturexGerman and American. 0aGerman fictionxHistory and criticism. 0aWomen in literature. 4aEnglish & American Literature. 4aGerman Literature. 4aWomen's & Gender Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Women Authors.2bisacsh  aAgency.  aAnglo-American.  aBecoming woman.  aFemale subjects.  aGender.  aGerman literary texts.  aIdentity.  aNeoliberalism.  aNovels.  aPostfeminism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311143106240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787441705423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787441705/original  a978-3-11-143106-2  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles